      <h1 style="font-size:2.25rem;margin-top:1rem;margin-bottom:0.5rem">Gas vs Electric Pressure Washer: Which One Belongs on Your Contracting Truck?</h1>
      <div style="color:#64748b;font-size:0.9rem">June 17, 2026 · 14 min read</div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>The gas vs electric pressure washer debate is not really a debate for commercial contractors — but that does not mean electric has no place on your truck. The right answer depends on the specific jobs you run, how many hours per week you wash, and whether the machine is a primary revenue generator or a secondary cleanup tool.</p>
      <p>This comparison cuts through the marketing. We compare real spec sheets, real run times, real maintenance costs, and real job-site logistics so you can decide which power source belongs in your trailer or truck bed.</p>

      <h2>The Spec Difference in One Table</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Spec</th><th>Gas (Pro Grade)</th><th>Electric (Pro Grade)</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Typical PSI</td><td>3400–4400</td><td>2000–2800</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Typical GPM</td><td>3.5–4.0</td><td>1.2–1.8</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Cleaning Units (PSI x GPM)</td><td>13,600–17,600</td><td>2,400–5,040</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Engine / Motor Type</td><td>Honda GX, 212cc–390cc</td><td>Universal brushless electric</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Pump Type</td><td>Triplex (AAA, belt-drive)</td><td>Axial cam or Wobble plate</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Run Time</td><td>Unlimited (fuel-dependent)</td><td>Limited by cord length / battery</td></tr>
