          <tr><td>Lifespan (Pro Use)</td><td>1,500–3,000+ hours</td><td>200–600 hours</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Initial Cost</td><td>$350 to $1,500</td><td>$150 to $500</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Cleaning Power: Gas Dominates by 3x to 5x</h2>
      <p>The single most important spec for commercial cleaning is cleaning units — the product of PSI and GPM. A pro-grade gas machine like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01KZSGRTE?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson 4400 PSI / 4.0 GPM Commercial Power Washer</a> delivers 17,600 cleaning units. A top-tier electric machine like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0BVGSX46M?tag=sciencesolved-20">Westinghouse ePX3500 Electric Pressure Washer</a> at 2500 PSI / 1.76 GPM delivers 4,400 cleaning units.</p>
      <p>That is not a small difference. On a 10,000-square-foot concrete parking lot, the gas machine completes the job in one shift. The electric machine takes three to four shifts, assuming you can even find an outlet. The labor cost alone makes the electric option uneconomical for any job large enough to make a contractor money.</p>

      <h2>Job-Site Logistics: Gas Is Self-Contained</h2>
      <p>A gas pressure washer carries its own fuel and needs nothing but a water supply. Fill the 1-gallon tank, pull the cord, and work. On a job site with no electricity — a new construction concrete pour, a remote commercial building, a farm or ranch washing station — the gas machine is the only option.</p>
      <p>Electric pressure washers need a 15-amp or 20-amp GFCI-protected outlet within 100 feet (maximum extension cord run for 14-gauge wire at full draw). Commercial job sites rarely have conveniently located exterior outlets. Running extension cords across active work areas creates tripping hazards and violates OSHA guidelines. Even if power is available, most job-site circuits are shared with saws, compressors, and lights — tripping a breaker mid-job costs billable time.</p>

      <h2>Where Electric Wins: Light Commercial, Noise-Sensitive, Indoor Work</h2>
      <p>Electric pressure washers have three genuine advantages for contractors:</p>
      <p><strong>1. Noise.</strong> Gas engines run at 85–95 dB. Electric motors run at 60–75 dB. In noise-sensitive environments — hospitals, hotels with guests, residential neighborhoods with strict noise ordinances, early-morning work — an electric washer lets you work without generating complaints. The Westinghouse ePX3500 at 2500 PSI is rated 4.6 stars specifically because it is powerful enough for light commercial work yet quiet enough for residential use.</p>
      <p><strong>2. Indoor operation.</strong> Gas engines produce carbon monoxide. Running a gas pressure washer in a parking garage, warehouse, or basement is a safety hazard without forced ventilation. Electric washers produce zero emissions and can operate indoors safely.</p>
      <p><strong>3. Maintenance.</strong> Electric washers require essentially no maintenance on the motor. No oil changes, no air filters, no spark plugs, no fuel stabilizer. For a contractor who uses a washer only a few hours per week, the maintenance-free aspect of electric is appealing.</p>

      <h2>The Hidden Cost of Electric: Pump Lifespan</h2>
      <p>Here is the detail most contractors miss: electric pressure washers use axial cam pumps or wobble-plate pumps that are not designed for extended run times. The pump on a $300 electric unit typically lasts 200–400 hours before the seals fail or the pump body cracks. Replacement cost is often 60–80 percent of the original machine price.</p>
      <p>Gas machines at the pro level use triplex plunger pumps. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07S7H6LGM?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson PS60869 PowerShot</a> uses an AAA Triplex pump. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01KZSGRTE?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson 4400 PSI commercial</a> uses a belt-drive AAA Triplex. These pumps are rebuildable — replaceable plungers, seals, valves, and packings — and are designed for 1,500 to 3,000+ hours of service. When the pump eventually wears, you rebuild it for a fraction of the replacement cost rather than throwing away the whole machine.</p>

      <h2>Run Time and Duty Cycle</h2>
      <p>Gas pressure washers run as long as you keep adding fuel. A 1-gallon tank at a Honda GX270 engine burning roughly 0.5 gallons per hour gives 2 hours of continuous run time. Refuel and keep going. The duty cycle on a belt-drive commercial gas machine is effectively 100 percent — it is designed to run all day.</p>
      <p>Electric washers have a duty cycle limitation built into the pump and motor. Most consumer electric washers are rated for intermittent duty — 3 minutes on, 3 minutes off. Even pro-sumer electric units typically recommend 5–10 minutes of continuous use followed by a cool-down period. This makes electric washers unsuitable for all-day commercial cleaning.</p>

      <h2>When Gas Is the Wrong Choice</h2>
      <p>Gas engines are heavy. A machine like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07S7H6LGM?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson PS60869</a> weighs around 130 pounds. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01KZSGRTE?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson 4400 commercial</a> is heavier with its belt-drive assembly. If you are carrying a pressure washer up stairs, onto rooftops for gutter cleaning, or into tight crawl spaces, gas machines are impractical. Electric units weigh 30–60 pounds and are genuinely portable by one person.</p>
      <p>For a window cleaning contractor working on multi-story buildings, a lightweight electric unit that runs on a bucket and extension cord is more practical than lugging a gas machine up a ladder. For a gutter cleaning pro who needs pressure to flush downspouts, a compact electric unit beats the weight penalty of gas.</p>

      <h2>Total Cost of Ownership Over 3 Years</h2>
      <p>To calculate real cost, factor in purchase price, maintenance, fuel/electricity, and expected replacement cycle:</p>
      <p><strong>Gas pro-grade (Simpson 4400 PSI commercial at $1,200–$1,500):</strong> Oil changes every 50 hours ($50/year in oil and filters). Fuel at roughly $2/hour of run time. Expect 3,000 hours of service life before major pump rebuild. Cost per hour of cleaning: approximately $0.80–$1.20 including maintenance and fuel.</p>
      <p><strong>Electric pro-sumer (Westinghouse ePX3500 at $300–$400):</strong> No engine maintenance. Electricity cost roughly $0.10/hour. Expect 400–600 hours before pump failure. At 600 hours, you need a second unit. Cost per hour of cleaning: approximately $0.70–$1.00 for the first 600 hours, then another $300+ for replacement. If you clean 20+ hours per week, you cycle through an electric unit every 6–8 months.</p>
      <p>The gas machine is substantially cheaper per hour for any contractor cleaning more than 10 hours per week. Below that threshold, electric can be cost-competitive.</p>

      <h2>The Fleet Strategy: One Gas, One Electric</h2>
      <p>Many commercial contractors run both. The gas machine lives on the trailer and handles the big concrete jobs, fleet washing, and heavy commercial work. A compact electric unit rides in the truck bed for quick calls — washing a single piece of equipment, cleaning a small patio as a value-add for a landscaping client, or handling noise-restricted early-morning work at a hotel.</p>
      <p>This dual-machine strategy maximizes uptime. If the gas machine goes down for maintenance, the electric unit keeps you in business for small jobs. If the electric pump fails, the gas machine still handles 90 percent of your workload.</p>
      <p>The best gas machine for this fleet approach is the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07S7H6LGM?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson PS60869 PowerShot</a> — proven Honda GX270 engine, reliable AAA Triplex pump, and enough cleaning power for all but the largest commercial flatwork jobs. Pair it with a <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0G6SXZ7VG?tag=sciencesolved-20">Professional 4200 PSI / 4 GPM</a> as a budget-friendly primary or backup, and a compact electric for the interior/noise-sensitive niche. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0G6SXZ7VG?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</p>

      <h2>Gas vs Electric: Decision Framework for Contractors</h2>
      <p>Here is a quick decision guide based on your primary use case:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Concrete cleaning / flatwork / parking lots:</strong> Gas only. The PSI and GPM requirements make electric uncompetitive.</li>
        <li><strong>Fleet washing / heavy equipment:</strong> Gas only. You need flow volume for degreaser and full job-site mobility.</li>
        <li><strong>House washing / soft washing:</strong> Either. Gas gives you the volume for large two-story homes. Electric works for single-story tract homes.</li>
        <li><strong>Window cleaning / gutter work:</strong> Electric preferred. Weight and portability matter more than maximum cleaning power.</li>
        <li><strong>Interior / parking garage / noise-sensitive:</strong> Electric only. Gas emissions and noise make it unsuitable.</li>
        <li><strong>New construction cleanup:</strong> Gas. No power on site. Gas runs off its own fuel supply.</li>
        <li><strong>Deck and fence restoration:</strong> Gas preferred. You need adjustable pressure control and enough flow for chemical application.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
      <p>For 90 percent of commercial contracting work, gas is the clear choice. The cleaning power advantage is 3x to 5x, the duty cycle is unlimited, and the total cost per hour is lower for any contractor cleaning more than a few hours per week. Gas machines are self-sufficient on job sites where power access is unpredictable or nonexistent.</p>
      <p>Electric pressure washers have a place in specific niches: indoor work, noise-sensitive environments, and applications where weight and portability are the primary concern. For a contractor who needs to show up and clean large surfaces efficiently, the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01KZSGRTE?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson 4400 PSI / 4.0 GPM commercial gas unit</a> or the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07S7H6LGM?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson PS60869 PowerShot</a> are the proven professional tools. Keep a compact electric unit in the truck for the edge cases, but make gas the backbone of your pressure washing operation.</p>

